0:["nHUYCTVjsWTesso99Tkid",[[["",{"children":["docs",{"children":["matching",{"children":["__PAGE__",{}]}]}]},"$undefined","$undefined",true],["",{"children":["docs",{"children":["matching",{"children":["__PAGE__",{},[["$L1",["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","h1",null,{"children":"The Matching Principle (Pred-09-5)"}],["$","blockquote",null,{"children":"Stable receivers in an environment with entropy H satisfy TI ≈ 1 / H."}],["$","p",null,{"children":"This is the core structural insight behind every TI recommendation. It comes from IMM Paper 9 and the RPCS-1 receiver dynamics framework."}],["$","h2",null,{"children":"What it means in practice"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"Environmental entropy H measures how frequently and unpredictably an environment changes. The Matching Principle says the Temporal Integration window (TI) of a stable receiver must scale inversely with H:"}],["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"High entropy (chaotic environment)"}]," → short TI. The agent should integrate only recent signals; old context is noise. Maps to short context windows, frequent grounding, small max_tokens."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Low entropy (stable environment)"}]," → long TI. The agent benefits from integrating deep history; old context is still relevant. Maps to long context windows, rolling summaries, large max_tokens."]}]]}],["$","h2",null,{"children":"The lookup table"}],["$","p",null,{"children":["The SDK implements this as a linear interpolation over a lookup table (from ",["$","code",null,{"children":"config/matching.json"}],"):"]}],["$","pre",null,{"children":["$","code",null,{"children":"H = 0.10 → TI = 90  (long deep integration)\nH = 0.25 → TI = 70  (stable integration)\nH = 0.50 → TI = 50  (balanced integration)\nH = 0.75 → TI = 30  (responsive integration)\nH = 0.95 → TI = 10  (rapid response)"}]}],["$","p",null,{"children":"For intermediate values, TI is linearly interpolated between the nearest table entries. For example, H = 0.2 (a \"stable\" environment) interpolates to TI ≈ 77."}],["$","h2",null,{"children":"Entropy levels"}],["$","pre",null,{"children":["$","code",null,{"children":"stable   → H = 0.20\nmoderate → H = 0.50\ndynamic  → H = 0.75\nchaotic  → H = 0.95"}]}],["$","h2",null,{"children":"The oscillation threshold"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The Matching Principle also implies a stability boundary: when SG × TI exceeds the oscillation threshold, the receiver is structurally near the oscillation regime — it integrates too long while amplifying too strongly, causing it to revisit decisions."}],["$","pre",null,{"children":["$","code",null,{"children":"oscillation threshold: SG × TI > 7000\n\n# Example: SG=80, TI=90 → product=7200 → oscillation warning"}]}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The tuner surfaces a warning whenever your configuration approaches this boundary."}],["$","h2",null,{"children":"Why this matters for LLMs"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"LLMs don't have a literal \"integration window\" in the receiver-dynamics sense, but the structural analogy holds:"}],["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":["TI maps to ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"how much context the model is given and expected to use"}]," — context window size, rolling-summary frequency, grounding injection rate."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["SG maps inversely to ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"temperature"}]," — a high-gain receiver amplifies signal differences, which in LLMs means low temperature (crisper, more deterministic outputs)."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["The oscillation threshold maps to the regime where a model with a very long context and very low temperature will start ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"re-analyzing the same evidence"}]," in loops."]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The cross-substrate conjecture (C-12-1 from RPCS-1) holds that the same receiver-dynamics framework applies across biological, artificial, and hybrid cognitive systems. Every production deployment of this SDK is a test of that conjecture."}]]}],null],null],null]},[null,["$","$L2",null,{"parallelRouterKey":"children","segmentPath":["children","docs","children","matching","children"],"error":"$undefined","errorStyles":"$undefined","errorScripts":"$undefined","template":["$","$L3",null,{}],"templateStyles":"$undefined","templateScripts":"$undefined","notFound":"$undefined","notFoundStyles":"$undefined"}]],null]},[[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"flex gap-12","children":[["$","aside",null,{"className":"hidden lg:block w-48 flex-shrink-0","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"sticky top-20","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs font-semibold text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3","children":"Documentation"}],["$","nav",null,{"className":"space-y-1","children":[["$","$L4","/docs",{"href":"/docs","className":"block px-3 py-1.5 text-sm rounded-lg transition-colors text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-200 hover:bg-gray-800","children":"Overview"}],["$","$L4","/docs/getting-started",{"href":"/docs/getting-started","className":"block px-3 py-1.5 text-sm rounded-lg transition-colors text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-200 hover:bg-gray-800","children":"Getting started"}],["$","$L4","/docs/primitives",{"href":"/docs/primitives","className":"block px-3 py-1.5 text-sm rounded-lg transition-colors text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-200 hover:bg-gray-800","children":"The five primitives"}],["$","$L4","/docs/matching",{"href":"/docs/matching","className":"block px-3 py-1.5 text-sm rounded-lg transition-colors text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-200 hover:bg-gray-800","children":"Matching principle"}],["$","$L4","/docs/regimes",{"href":"/docs/regimes","className":"block px-3 py-1.5 text-sm rounded-lg transition-colors text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-200 hover:bg-gray-800","children":"Stability regimes"}],["$","$L4","/docs/platforms",{"hre